1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,830
Stories have the power of captivating in a way that facts just cannot compete.

2
00:00:04,830 --> 00:00:06,630
When you're presenting your findings,

3
00:00:06,630 --> 00:00:08,295
make sure to tell a story.

4
00:00:08,295 --> 00:00:10,275
When telling a story about data,

5
00:00:10,275 --> 00:00:12,660
you should start with a compelling question.

6
00:00:12,660 --> 00:00:15,375
If you are providing in entire presentation,

7
00:00:15,375 --> 00:00:18,615
supplement your question with engaging visuals.

8
00:00:18,615 --> 00:00:22,480
Continue to motivate your question with additional examples or

9
00:00:22,480 --> 00:00:24,810
deeper questions to help your audience further

10
00:00:24,810 --> 00:00:28,215
engage and understand the context of your question.

11
00:00:28,215 --> 00:00:32,010
Repetition of the problem is a good thing,

12
00:00:32,010 --> 00:00:35,100
it can be simple and clearly explicit.

13
00:00:35,100 --> 00:00:37,890
Repetition in visuals and audio cues

14
00:00:37,890 --> 00:00:41,040
helps your audience move your question to long-term memory.

15
00:00:41,040 --> 00:00:45,530
Now provide the data that supports an answer to the question.

16
00:00:45,530 --> 00:00:48,670
Highlight the answers so that no one can miss it.

17
00:00:48,670 --> 00:00:51,975
Conclude with a call to action for your audience.

18
00:00:51,975 --> 00:00:55,370
Data by itself does not move people to take action.

19
00:00:55,370 --> 00:00:57,295
You must motivate the action.

20
00:00:57,295 --> 00:00:59,675
Data can assist in your conclusion,

21
00:00:59,675 --> 00:01:04,390
but you must provide the context for the next steps for your audience to take.

22
00:01:04,390 --> 00:01:06,125
In the next concept,

23
00:01:06,125 --> 00:01:09,500
you will see two versions of the same presentation with

24
00:01:09,500 --> 00:01:14,190
the same information and you can decide who tells a better story.

